@kyleknap Yes, it does read `role_arn` from `~/.aws/config`, but that is the issue. There is no need to start a new assume-role role session (possible asking for an MFA code when MFA is configured) when one is already available in `~/.aws/credentials`.

See the [source code](https://github.com/boto/botocore/blob/develop/botocore/credentials.py#L59-L82). With `aws-cli` this behaviour is obscured because `AssumeRoleProvider` is caching (in `~/.aws/cli/cache`, not `~/.aws/cache` as incorrectly stated in the docs you linked), but you'll experience it with any other program using botocore with this default provider chain in `get_credentials()`.

Moving `SharedCredentialsProvider` above `AssumeRoleProvider` fixes this and still passes all the botocore tests.

@kylemacfarlane you are correct that without the AVS/CVV coming back in the response, you are limited to the Fraud Filters for having control over what is done with transactions that match/don't match AVS/CVV.  Keep in mind, however, that these transactions are still screened by PayPal regardless if the Fraud Filters are being used.  The Fraud Filters just give the account holder an extra bit of control over the transactions that the card issuing bank and PayPal have approved.  

To answer your question directly - yes, if you want the extra control over REST credit card transactions in regards to AVS/CVV, you will need to upgrade to the Advanced Filters.  @jziaja is currently working with the correct team internally to see about adding these fields to the REST CC response, but unfortunately we don't have a timeline to provide as of yet.  

As for the cost(s) associated with the advanced filter upgrade/usage, that is not something that we can answer as it's not a technical question related to SDK functionality.  For those cost related questions, I'll need to defer you to our Customer Support team which can be reached by clicking 'Contact Us' at the bottom of any PayPal page.

