This should be in the docs somewhere.

For anyone who comes across this, here's how you do it in 2.0:

`middleware.py`

```
from .loaders import Loaders

class LoaderMiddleware:	
	def resolve(self, next, root, info, **args):
		if not hasattr(info.context, 'loaders'):
			info.context.loaders = Loaders()
		return next(root, info, **args)
```

`settings.py`

```
GRAPHENE = {
    'MIDDLEWARE': [
        'middlewares.LoaderMiddleware'
    ]
}
```

Access the loaders in the resolvers using `info.context`:

```
class Thing(DjangoObjectType):
    class Meta:
        model = ThingModel
    
    def resolve_XXX(self, info):
        return info.context.loaders.XXX_loader.load(self.XXX_id)
```

I think the test could be simplified so it doesn't require a separate module. It should be possible to pack up everything into a function within the existing test module. Something like:

```c++
m.def("test_matching_holder_type", []() {
    struct Base { };
    struct Derived : Base { };

    try {
        py::class_<Base>(m, "Base");
        py::class_<Derived, std::shared_ptr<Derived>, Base>(m, "Derived")
            .def(py::init<>());
    } catch (std::runtime_error &) {
        return true;
    }
    return false;
});
```

```python
assert test_matching_holder_type() is True
```

It might be possible to simplify `void_holder` to a pure type metafunction:
```c++
template <typename... Ts>
struct void_holder<std::unique_ptr<Ts...>> {
    using type = std::unique_ptr<void>;
};
```
where the `typeid` just moves outside:
```c++
tinfo->void_holder_type = &typeid(detail::void_holder<holder_type>::type);
```

A more generic approach for `void_holder` might also be worth considering so that users don't need to provide specializations in most cases:
```c++
template <typename T, typename SFINAE = void>
struct void_holder {
    using type = void;
}

template <typename...> using void_t = void;

template <template<typename...> class Holder, typename... Ts>
struct void_holder<Holder<Ts...>, void_t<Holder<void>>> {
    using type = Holder<void>;
};
```

The `void_t` SFINAE would make sure `Holder<void>` is a valid type. But I'm just thinking out loud here and this might not even compile properly.

@gyroninja, have you manually done any modifications to the `/etc/letsencrypt` directory? While we should probably have more validity checks in our code, Certbot often behaves incorrectly if `/etc/letsencrypt` is put in an invalid state.

Also, it'd be useful to see all of the logs in `/var/log/letsencrypt`. That way we can track when the cert was created to when the symlinks were created incorrectly.

In every case of this I've seen (see https://community.letsencrypt.org/t/certbot-live-symlinks-not-updating-as-expected-new-certificate-available-but-not-used/35181/11), the user had improperly modified `/etc/letsencrypt`.

Looks like the issue is that [pyodbc is not thread safe](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1537809/python-multiprocessing-and-database-access-with-pyodbc-is-not-safe).

This means that Ray cannot share the pyodbc connection object across tasks. A fix would be to create a new connection in each task:
```python
@ray.remote
def oneSynchronize(customerSQL):
 connexion = pypyodbc.connect("your connection string here")
 return read_sql(customerSQL,connexion)
```

